{"key":"post-8546633","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8546633</id>\n<content>The 'old' method was to apply the casing layer at the time the substrate was prepared, therefore you can case at 0% colonization if you want to.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, since on the scale of time, mushroom growing remains in its infancy, we're still learning as we go along.&amp;nbsp; We've found that if you colonize your substrate first, and then case it at full colonization, you'll be a bit more likely to get an even pinset.&amp;nbsp; Don't stress it though, it's not about contamination.&amp;nbsp; You can case the day your mix your spawn into the substrate if you wish.&amp;nbsp; The casing layer will colonize as the substrate does, if you use that method.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8547770</next>\n<prev>8546496</prev>\n<first>8545035</first>\n<last>8554353</last>\n<when>1214052930</when>\n<utime>06/21/08 03:55 PM</utime>\n</post>"}